<p><font class="headermed">News Release</font></p>

<h5>New York<br>EMPLOYMENT STANDARDS ADMINISTRATION/WAGE AND HOUR DIVISION<br>Contact: Chester J. Fultz<br>212-337-2319<br>NY 147 - April 9, 1997<br>For Release: Immediately</h5>

<h4>PIZZA HUT CHAIN CITED BY U.S. LABOR DEPARTMENT FOR WILLFULLY HAZARDOUS CHILD 
  LABOR VIOLATIONS; $194,400 CIVIL PENALTY ASSESSED </h4>
<p> Pizza Hut of America has been assessed a total of $194,400 in civil money 
  penalties by the U.S. Labor Department for violations of child labor laws at 
  26 of its restaurants in and around New York City. Pizza Hut of America is a 
  subsidiary of Pizza Hut, Inc., 14841 Dallas Parkway, Dallas, Texas. </p>
<p> The violations of regulations prohibiting the operation of hazardous equipment 
  by minors were disclosed during inspections of 32 Pizza Hut restaurants in New 
  York City and Westchester, Rockland, Orange and Ulster counties, conducted between 
  June, 1996 and March, 1997. </p>
<p> According to Bruce Sullivan, assistant regional administrator of the Labor 
  Department&#146;s Wage and Hour Division, a total of 81 violations involving 
  75 minors were documented through employee interviews and payroll records. &quot;All 
  Pizza Hut stores are equipped with a dough mixer, a piece of equipment specifically 
  prohibited to be operated by anyone under the age of 18. The company has paid 
  civil penalties for this in the past and has stipulated full compliance in the 
  future, but has willfully and knowingly permitted the violations to continue. 
  Our investigators found 68 instances of minors operating or cleaning dough mixers 
  or dough rollers at 25 locations.&quot;</p>
<p> Sullivan noted that the violations occurred despite warning signs attached 
  to all the machines and a written agreement all minor employees must sign indicating 
  they know they must not touch dough mixers or dough rollers. </p>
<p> &quot;We also identified seven cases of 17-year-old employees working as pizza 
  delivery drivers, in violation of the order prohibiting operation of a motor 
  vehicle, and three cases of 16-and-17 year-old employees using electric slicing 
  machines,&quot; Sullivan said. </p>
<p> The department&#146;s legal action against the firm follows an investigation 
  by the Wage and Hour Division&#146;s Hudson Valley Area Office, located at 140 
  Grand Street, Suite 304, White Plains, New York, telephone (914) 682-6348. </p>
<p align="center"> ***********</p>
<p> For a list of the specific Pizza Hut locations found in violation call the 
  above contact number.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
